      <!-- 1. Definition -->
      <h2 id="what-is-aeo" class="anchor-top">What Is Answer Engine Optimisation?</h2>
      <p><strong>Answer Engine Optimisation (AEO) is the practice of structuring website content so that answer engines can extract and surface it as a direct response to user queries.</strong> These answer engines include Google's featured snippets, AI Overviews, Microsoft Copilot, ChatGPT, Perplexity, voice assistants like Alexa and Siri, and any interface that delivers answers rather than links.</p>
      <p>The term emerged as search evolved beyond ten blue links. When a user asks "what is the boiling point of water," Google does not simply list pages about boiling points. It extracts the answer — 100 degrees Celsius — and presents it directly. AEO is the discipline of ensuring your content is the source that gets selected for that extraction.</p>
      <p>Unlike traditional search engine optimisation, which focuses on ranking position within a results page, AEO focuses on <em>selection</em>. The goal is not to rank first in a list of links. The goal is to become the answer itself.</p>
      <p>This distinction matters commercially. Brands that appear in answer boxes, AI Overviews, and voice responses gain authority and visibility that no amount of link-list ranking can replicate. The user does not choose between ten options. The answer engine chooses for them — and AEO determines whether that choice is you.</p>

      <!-- 2. How AEO Works -->
      <h2 id="how-aeo-works" class="anchor-top">How AEO Works</h2>
      <p><strong>Answer engines work by identifying the most authoritative, clearly structured response to a query and presenting it without requiring the user to click through.</strong> Understanding the mechanics behind this selection process is essential to optimising for it.</p>

      <h3>Featured Snippets</h3>
      <p>Featured snippets are the original answer engine. Google selects a passage, list, or table from a web page and displays it above the organic results in "position zero." The selection algorithm favours content that directly and concisely answers the query, uses clear heading structures, and comes from pages with established topical authority.</p>
      <p>There are three primary snippet formats: paragraph snippets (a concise text block answering a definitional or explanatory query), list snippets (ordered or unordered lists answering "how to" or "best of" queries), and table snippets (structured data comparisons). Each format requires different content structures to trigger selection.</p>

      <h3>AI Overviews</h3>
      <p>Google's AI Overviews represent the next evolution. Rather than extracting a single passage, the AI synthesises information from multiple sources into a generated response. Your content can be cited as one of several contributing sources, or it can be the primary source the AI draws from.</p>
      <p>AI Overviews favour content that demonstrates expertise through specific data points, original research, and clear entity relationships. Generic content that restates common knowledge is rarely cited. The AI needs a reason to reference <em>your</em> page rather than its own training data.</p>

      <h3>Voice Assistants and Conversational AI</h3>
      <p>Voice search through Alexa, Google Assistant, and Siri operates on a single-answer model. There is no "page two." The assistant selects one source, reads the answer, and the interaction ends. This makes AEO especially critical for voice-first queries, where the stakes are binary: you are either the answer or you are invisible.</p>

      <h3>LLM-Powered Search</h3>
      <p>Platforms like Perplexity, ChatGPT with browsing, and Microsoft Copilot use large language models to generate answers with cited sources. These systems evaluate content for factual accuracy, source authority, recency, and structural clarity. They tend to cite content that makes definitive statements backed by evidence rather than hedged, opinion-light prose.</p>

      <!-- 3. AEO vs GEO -->
      <h2 id="aeo-vs-geo" class="anchor-top">AEO vs GEO: How They Relate</h2>
      <p><strong>AEO is a subset of <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Generative Engine Optimisation (GEO)</a>.</strong> The two disciplines are related but differ in scope and application.</p>
      <p>AEO focuses specifically on answer-box and direct-answer interfaces: featured snippets, knowledge panels, voice responses, and People Also Ask expansions. The optimisation target is a discrete answer to a discrete question.</p>
      <p>GEO encompasses the broader challenge of making your brand visible across all AI-driven search surfaces. This includes LLM citation in conversational AI, generative search experiences like Google's AI Overviews, and the emerging landscape of AI agents that autonomously research topics and recommend solutions.</p>
      <p>Think of it as a hierarchy. GEO is the umbrella discipline. AEO is the branch that addresses the specific challenge of being selected as a direct answer. Every AEO tactic is a GEO tactic, but GEO includes strategies — like entity authority building, LLM training data optimisation, and multi-source citation strategies — that go beyond the scope of answer-box optimisation.</p>
      <p>If your primary concern is featured snippets and voice search answers, AEO is your focus. If you want comprehensive visibility across ChatGPT, Perplexity, Copilot, and AI Overviews, you need the full <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO framework</a>.</p>

      <!-- 4. AEO vs Traditional SEO -->
      <h2 id="aeo-vs-seo" class="anchor-top">AEO vs Traditional SEO</h2>
      <p><strong>AEO changes the success metric from ranking position to answer selection, but it does not replace traditional SEO.</strong> The two disciplines are complementary, and AEO performs best when built on top of strong SEO foundations. For a fuller comparison of how AI search differs from traditional search, see our <a href="/geo-vs-seo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO vs SEO guide</a>.</p>

