      <h3>What Stays the Same</h3>
      <p>Technical SEO fundamentals remain essential. Crawlability, page speed, mobile responsiveness, HTTPS, and clean site architecture are prerequisites for both SEO and AEO. Answer engines will not select content from pages they cannot efficiently crawl and render.</p>
      <p>Topical authority still matters. Answer engines prefer content from domains that demonstrate comprehensive expertise in their subject area. A site with fifty deeply researched articles on home energy is more likely to be selected as the answer source for a heat pump query than a generalist blog with one article on the topic.</p>

      <h3>What Changes</h3>
      <p>Content structure becomes paramount. Traditional SEO tolerates buried answers and long introductions. AEO demands that the core answer appears early, clearly, and in a format that machines can extract. The "inverted pyramid" — leading with the definitive answer before expanding into supporting detail — is the primary structural pattern for AEO content.</p>

      <!-- 5. AEO Best Practices -->
      <h2 id="best-practices" class="anchor-top">AEO Best Practices</h2>
      <p><strong>Effective AEO follows ten principles that make content machine-extractable, authoritative, and structurally clear.</strong> These practices are not theoretical — they reflect the patterns consistently observed in content that answer engines select.</p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-8 space-y-4">
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">1. Lead with a definitive answer</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Every section that targets an answer query should open with a clear, concise statement of 40-60 words that directly answers the question. This is the passage answer engines extract. Place it immediately after the heading, before any context or elaboration. Avoid introductory preamble.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">2. Use question-based headings</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Structure your H2s and H3s as the exact questions users ask. Answer engines match queries to headings before evaluating the body text beneath them. "What is answer engine optimisation?" is more AEO-effective than "Overview of AEO" because it mirrors the natural language query.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">3. Implement FAQ schema</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">FAQPage structured data explicitly marks up question-answer pairs for machine consumption. This is not optional for AEO — it is the strongest signal you can send that your content is structured for direct-answer extraction. Include 4-8 genuine FAQs per page, each with a complete, self-contained answer.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">4. Structure content for extraction</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Use lists for process-based queries ("how to"), tables for comparison queries ("X vs Y"), and concise paragraphs for definitional queries ("what is"). Match your content format to the snippet type your target query triggers. Check existing SERPs to identify which format Google currently prefers for each query.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">5. Establish entity clarity</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Answer engines need to understand what entities your content discusses and how they relate. Use consistent terminology throughout. If you refer to "answer engine optimisation," do not switch to "AEO" without first establishing the abbreviation. Mention related entities (Google, featured snippets, AI Overviews) to build semantic context.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">6. Build source authority signals</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Answer engines preferentially select content from authoritative sources. Cite original data, reference specific studies, include author credentials, and link to primary sources. Pages that aggregate information without adding original insight are rarely selected. Demonstrate why your perspective adds unique value.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">7. Optimise for voice search patterns</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Voice queries are longer and more conversational than typed queries. They frequently begin with "how," "what," "why," "when," and "who." Write answers that sound natural when read aloud. Keep answer paragraphs under 50 words for voice snippet selection — assistants will not read extended passages.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">8. Target People Also Ask boxes</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">People Also Ask (PAA) is an answer engine in its own right. Each PAA expansion pulls content from a different source, creating multiple opportunities for visibility. Research the PAA questions that appear for your target keywords and create content that answers each one with a dedicated heading and concise response.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">9. Keep content fresh and accurate</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Answer engines deprioritise stale content. Regularly update statistics, dates, and factual claims. Include a visible "last updated" date. For topics that change frequently — pricing, regulations, technology capabilities — set a quarterly review schedule and update the dateModified in your Article schema.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">10. Make your content crawlable by AI</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Ensure your robots.txt allows access to AI crawlers (GPTBot, ClaudeBot, PerplexityBot). Provide an <code class="bg-ink-800 text-[#BFE9E1] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-[var(--line)]">llms.txt</code> file that summarises your site's expertise and structure. Use semantic HTML — <code class="bg-ink-800 text-[#BFE9E1] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-[var(--line)]">&lt;article&gt;</code>, <code class="bg-ink-800 text-[#BFE9E1] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-[var(--line)]">&lt;section&gt;</code>, <code class="bg-ink-800 text-[#BFE9E1] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-[var(--line)]">&lt;nav&gt;</code> — rather than generic <code class="bg-ink-800 text-[#BFE9E1] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-[var(--line)]">&lt;div&gt;</code> wrappers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 6. AEO Tools -->
      <h2 id="aeo-tools" class="anchor-top">AEO Tools</h2>
      <p><strong>AEO requires tools that reveal how answer engines interact with your content, not just where you rank.</strong> The traditional rank tracker is necessary but insufficient. You need to track answer selection, not just position.</p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="card p-5">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-ink-50">SERP Feature Trackers</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Tools like Semrush, Ahrefs, and SE Ranking track featured snippet ownership, People Also Ask appearances, and knowledge panel presence. These show you where you currently hold answer positions and where competitors own them.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-5">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-ink-50">Schema Validators</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Google's Rich Results Test and Schema.org Validator confirm your structured data is correctly implemented. Invalid schema is worse than no schema — it signals unreliable content to answer engines.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-5">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-ink-50">AI Search Monitors</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Platforms like Otterly.AI, Peec AI, and Profound monitor how your brand appears in AI-generated answers across ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Google AI Overviews. These are the emerging standard for AEO measurement.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-5">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-ink-50">Google Search Console</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">GSC's search appearance filters show impressions and clicks specifically from featured snippets and other SERP features. This is your primary free tool for tracking AEO performance on Google.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-5">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-ink-50">Content Optimisation Platforms</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Clearscope, SurferSEO, and Frase analyse the semantic patterns in content that currently holds answer positions. They help you structure content to match the patterns answer engines prefer for specific query types.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 7. AEO for Different Business Types -->
      <h2 id="business-types" class="anchor-top">AEO for Different Business Types</h2>
      <p><strong>AEO strategy varies by business type because different industries trigger different answer formats.</strong> The approach for a local service business differs fundamentally from that of a SaaS company or an e-commerce brand.</p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-8 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="card card-hover p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Local Services</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Local businesses should optimise for "near me" and "best [service] in [location]" answer queries. Google Business Profile optimisation, local FAQ schema, and review structured data are critical. Voice search disproportionately favours local queries — a significant share of voice searches carry local intent.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card card-hover p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">E-commerce</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Product-related queries trigger shopping-specific answer formats. Optimise Product schema, include pricing and availability data, and target comparison queries with structured tables. "Best [product] for [use case]" queries are high-value AEO targets for e-commerce brands.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card card-hover p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">SaaS and Technology</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Technology companies should focus on definitional queries ("what is [feature/concept]"), how-to content, and comparison queries ("X vs Y"). Technical documentation with clear code examples and step-by-step instructions performs exceptionally well in both featured snippets and AI citations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card card-hover p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Professional Services</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Law firms, accountancies, and consultancies should target informational queries that precede commercial intent. "How much does [service] cost," "do I need [service]," and "what is the process for [action]" are high-value AEO targets that position the firm as the authority before the prospect begins comparing providers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card card-hover p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Healthcare and YMYL</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">Your Money, Your Life content faces elevated scrutiny from answer engines. Medical, financial, and legal content must demonstrate E-E-A-T (Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trust) through author credentials, peer-reviewed citations, and clear disclaimers. Answer engines are increasingly cautious about which sources they select for health-related answers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card card-hover p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Publishers and Media</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-400 leading-relaxed">News and media organisations should optimise for recency-sensitive queries. Timely, fact-checked reporting with clear datelines and NewsArticle schema receives preferential treatment in answer formats. Evergreen explainer content with regular updates targets the long-tail of informational queries.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 8. Getting Started -->
      <h2 id="getting-started" class="anchor-top">Getting Started with AEO</h2>
      <p><strong>Starting AEO does not require rebuilding your content strategy from scratch.</strong> It requires auditing your existing content through an answer-engine lens and making structural adjustments that improve machine extractability. Our <a href="/aeo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO services</a> cover each phase described below.</p>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Audit your current featured snippet presence.</strong> Use GSC and a SERP tracker to identify which queries you already appear in answer boxes for, and which competitor holds the snippets you should own.</li>
        <li><strong>Identify high-value answer queries.</strong> Filter your keyword list for question-based queries with featured snippet or AI Overview presence. Prioritise queries where you already rank in the top five — these are the easiest to convert into answer positions.</li>
        <li><strong>Restructure your top pages.</strong> Add clear question headings, lead each section with a 40-60 word definitive answer, and implement FAQ schema. This single change can shift content from "ranked but not selected" to "owning the answer box."</li>
        <li><strong>Implement structured data.</strong> Article, FAQPage, HowTo, and Product schemas are the minimum. Validate every implementation with Google's Rich Results Test before deployment.</li>
        <li><strong>Monitor and iterate.</strong> Track answer selection weekly. When you lose an answer position, analyse what the new holder does differently. AEO is a continuous optimisation process, not a one-time implementation.</li>
      </ol>

    </article>
